label chapter12:

    # [Scene: Abandoned Promenade | Late Afternoon — Overcast]

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Distant cello, low and slow]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The soft slap of residual waves against revetments; a chain-link gate thudding somewhere down the strip]
    "You arrived here knowing both roads that could have led you—preserve the nodes, accept staged redevelopment—and you carried the taste of each in your mouth like iron. The particulars of past arguments blur now; whether you"
    "argued for locks on buyouts or for clauses in redevelopment, the timetable collapsed the same way: investments arrived faster than your community could bind them, and decisions made with deadlines favored the speed of capital over"
    "the slow, stubborn work of repair."
    "The promenade is the proof. What used to be a mishmash of fish-smoke shops and homecraft stalls is now a display—gleaming terraces, curated tide-line exhibits, an expensive café that uses reclaimed driftwood as décor while a"
    "security guard in a windbreaker checks a tablet. The air smells of lemon polish and diesel, not kelp and fry oil. The sea keeps the same indifferent rhythm, but the edges of the town answer differently."
    "You run a thumb over the compass dent in your jacket without thinking—its brass warm from the sun that breaks through a fringe of cloud for a single weak moment—and watch a family walk past with"
    "cardboard boxes stamped by a municipal relocation contractor. They avoid your eyes in the way that people avoid opening a wound in public."

    "Gracie 'Nan' Armitage" "They'll make museums out of what they couldn't keep,"
    show maya_armitage at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_armitage "Museums don't keep the smell of fish or the way the dock plank creaks under a child's foot.' (You keep your voice low; the cove doesn't need performance now.) 'They keep curated versions."
    "Gracie 'Nan' Armitage: (She exhales through her nose) 'Curated versions are easier to sell. Easier to forget.'"
    "You want to argue—about clauses, trust mechanisms, the sanctity of a communal process—but the private security van rolls by and the guard nods at Nan as if recognizing a species rather than a neighbor. Her mouth tightens. You feel the thing you fought against become an artifact before your eyes."

    menu:
        "Take Nan's hand":
            "You step forward and fold her fingers into yours. For a second her knuckles go slack and then squeeze, an old, mine-sure grip. The contact is a small, human defiance."
        "Stand beside her, silent":
            "You stand shoulder-to-shoulder, sharing the same horizon. Silence is its own solidarity; sometimes your presence must hold the grief uncluttered by words."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue"
    hide maya_armitage

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A phone buzzes inside your jacket; distant laughter from the curated boardwalk feels like an insult and a lullaby at once]
    "Jonah Reyes appears at the mouth of the promenade—coat open, hair damp from the sea-spray. He moves with that patient gait he always had; his eyes take in the lights, the storefronts, the contractors with coastal-issue clipboards and branded hardhats. He tries a wry smile that doesn't land."
    show jonah_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "They're calling it 'revitalization,'' he says, half teasing, half furious. 'Like they're rescuing us from ourselves. Everything has to sound palatable."
    "Maya Armitage: (There's a sharp edge in your chest that answers) 'They've always sold rescue as mercy.'"
    "Jonah Reyes: (He laughs, a small, bitter sound) 'And sometimes rescue shows up with a price tag. Nan—' (He hesitates, watching her braid.) 'She still remembers the nets my grandfather mended here. The work isn't a display for their glossy brochures, Maya.'"
    "You exchange a look long enough to carry decades. Jonah's hands fidget with the rope bracelet at his wrist, the way he does when he's deciding not to stir old grief into new courage."

    jonah_reyes "I can teach in the city for a while. There's a program—steady pay, nights on call, something for the boy cousins. They'll think it's sensible. I...' (He stops; his voice catches, then steadies.) 'You'll keep the records, right?"
    "Maya Armitage: (Because this is the knot you don't know how to cut) 'I will document. I'll keep the trust documents, the affidavits, the photos—everything. I won't let them sanitize every memory into a footnote.'"

    jonah_reyes "Promise me you'll... keep some of it just for us."
    "Maya Armitage: (You want to promise more than you can give. You hold out both hands; there is no simple binding.) 'I promise I'll try.'"
    "Jonah smiles in that way that crumples the sunlight and tells you he's trying to be brave. You watch him walk away toward the bus stop with a case of workshop tools strapped across his back—tools"
    "that once mended boats and now will patch a life in another town. The distance already begins to stretch."
    hide jonah_reyes

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The wet slap of his boots grows faint; a gull cries]
    # [Scene: Reclaimed Marsh Restoration Site | Night — Storm Approaching]

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: High strings, nervous and thin]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Wind beginning to run like a ruler across marsh grass; the first cold rain]
    "You climb the narrow boardwalk toward the restoration site, notebook heavy in your arms. The restoration plots that once hummed with careful hand-plantings now show gaps—saplings collapsed, coir rolls begun to fray. Where the new commercial"
    "wall meets the marsh, there is a seam: a band of geotextile cloth tied in a knot with contractor tape. Someone stapled a 'Work In Progress' sign and left."
    "Rafi Chen's sketchbook is splayed in the vestibule of the field tent; his blue ink diagrams tremble under a plastic sheet. He looks at you without surprise and then with the gravity of someone who has been carrying a forecast no one wanted to read."
    show rafi_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rafi_chen "They reallocated the seal funds,' he says. 'Investors wanted the promenade to look safe for ribbon-cutting tomorrow. That money came from the marsh budget.' (His mouth tightens; he has the neat hands of someone who builds solutions and is now forced to unbuild a part of them.) 'We can do emergency buoyant collars, but—"
    show maya_armitage at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_armitage "But it's temporary."

    rafi_chen "Temporary collapses faster in salt water. We can jury-rig, but if the storm hits hard—"
    "You walk the lines between the planted grasses, feeling the wet through your boots. The air is iodine and metal: salt and the smell of nearby fleet engines. The storm arrives sooner than hoped; rain begins to bead on the exposed pages of your notebook."
    "Evelyn Hart is there under a canopied truck light, clipboard in hand, her trench coat buttoned up against the rain. Up close, she looks smaller than in council chambers, but her voice carries the same clean efficiency."
    show evelyn_hart at center:
        zoom 0.7

    evelyn_hart "We prioritized the visible infrastructure,' she says without apology. 'Investors need confidence. The boardwalk is symbolic; if it fails their confidence, we lose all leverage.' (Her fingers don't tremble when she taps her pen.) 'Ideally, we'd restore both simultaneously. Reality demanded a choice."
    "Maya Armitage: (You hold something back—rage, grief, a litany of missed meetings—and let your voice be measured) 'You chose investors over marshes. The marsh is not symbolic to those who sleep with its tide lines. It is their lifeline.'"
    "Evelyn Hart: (She meets your eyes, and a moment of something like guilt flickers—but it is quickly folded away) 'We seeded a trust for relocations—legal protections. We didn't put them on the table as performance metrics"
    "for a ribbon-cutting. I didn't like that we had to pick. I negotiated what I could.'"

    maya_armitage "Did you consider asking for more time? For staged allotments that guaranteed restoration before commercialization?"
    "Evelyn Hart: (Her jaw works) 'I asked. The board placed timelines on deliverables. This region had to show immediate returns to secure larger grants. I argued for the marsh, for the trust—' (She stops. Her eyes flick toward the failing check-dams.) 'I did what I could with what I had.'"
    "The rain thickens. The marsh reeds whistle in the wind like a chorus of thin voices."
    "Maya Armitage: (You step closer, voice low) 'What you did had consequences.'"

    evelyn_hart "Consequences are part of policy.' (She says it like a fact: neither apology nor boast.) 'If you want to litigate, you'll have to show malfeasance, not just bad outcomes."

    maya_armitage "This isn't just bad outcomes,' you say. 'This is people's homes, histories. We will tell this story with names, with dates, with photos. We'll show the sequence."
    "Evelyn Hart: (She studies you as if weighing whether you're a threat or an ally, then gives a small, formal nod.) 'I don't want the town to be a parade for inequitable adaptation, Maya. If that"
    "happens, I will answer for it.' (There is something like a promise wrapped in the legalese; it is not comfort, but it is acknowledgment.)"

    menu:
        "Record Evelyn's words on your phone":
            "You press record and the light blinks red. Her measured sentences register: evidence, and a brittle warmth of truth. You feel the authority of the moment—both weapon and shield."
        "Refuse to record; take notes by hand":
            "You pull a pen and write, slow and deliberate. The ink smudges in the rain, but your handwriting bears the tremor of the hour—messy, human, verifiable in its imperfection."

