    "Continue"
    "Rafi pulls the tarp down over the kit with a practiced motion and looks at you both, tired and raw."

    rafi_chen "If the storm hits, the marsh won't be the only thing we lose,' he says. 'Those families we tried to keep in place? The ones moved to the temporary barracks? Their support networks are gone. They'll be the most at risk."
    "Maya Armitage: (You think of the faces you've catalogued—older neighbors who couldn't relocate fast enough, young parents trying to salvage heirlooms from damp boxes—every entry a small elegy) 'We did what we could.' The statement tastes like ash. 'But what we couldn't do will have names.'"
    # [Scene: Promenade | Early Dawn — After the Storm]
    hide rafi_chen
    hide maya_armitage
    hide evelyn_hart

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Solo piano, sparse and aching]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The slow drip of water from eaves; a distant megaphone announcing a cleanup schedule]
    "The storm came overnight and found the weakest seams. The partially funded marsh bulged and lost sections; the check-dams gave where the current found leverage. One relocation cluster—temporary housing pitched too close to an undermined berm—suffered"
    "a partial failure before crews could reinforce it. No lives lost where the managed retreat succeeded, thank the measured plans and a lot of overnight heroics. But loss is measured in more ways than lives."
    "You walk the promenade at first light and find residents who arrived early, forming a chain to carry quilts and damp boxes to dry platforms. They move like a community excavating its own memory. You step in to help, hands used to work that saves more than it comforts."
    "Relocated Families: (A voice from a group) 'We were told safety would follow soon.' (Someone laughs a small, sharp laugh.) 'Soon was supposed to be a timeline, not a betrayal.'"
    show maya_armitage at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_armitage "We tried to make sure 'soon' was enforceable.' (You meet their eyes because they demand it.) 'If anyone here needs help with affidavits or claims, I'm on the table today. We'll catalog every item, every damage. I will not let these vanish into a ledger."
    "Someone gives you a tired, grateful look; someone else looks away. The cove is full of compromised loyalties—those who stayed, those who left, those who came back. You have documents to prove misallocation; you have photographs"
    "of the failed berms; you have witness statements that will form the spine of the story you refuse to let the developers fold into a glossy brochure."
    "Gracie 'Nan' Armitage sits on an overturned crate near a small driftwood shrine where people have left shells and carved name tags. Her braid is even thinner after the wind and rain. She lifts a hand, and you kneel to take it."
    "Gracie 'Nan' Armitage: (She whispers) 'We made songlines out of work and tide. They've turned the song into a lecture you pay to hear. They took the living off the water and put displays of it behind glass.'"
    "Maya Armitage: (A hot surge of anger and grief pushes through) 'They took pieces. We kept others. We can't unmake what happened, Nan. But we can name it.'"

    "Gracie 'Nan' Armitage" "Names keep people alive. Don't forget how to name, child."
    "You take a breath that catches the salt in it. You think of Jonah—packing tools into a van and leaving a line of promise stretched thin across a map—and you think of all the neighbors whose"
    "livelihoods unravel in slow, bureaucratic motions. Love and logistics no longer fit neatly in the same sentence."
    "Your phone rings. Jonah Reyes's name blinks on the screen: an international operator prefix you weren't prepared for. You answer."
    "Jonah Reyes: (Over the line; his voice rougher for distance) 'Hey,' he says simply."

    maya_armitage "Jonah.' (You hear the tar in your own voice.) 'How's the job? The first week okay?"
    show jonah_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "It's... steady.' (A pause.) 'My cousin got sick. I took overtime. The pay helps. I feel like I moved into an engine room.' (He forces a laugh you don't hear on the other end.) 'I miss the smell of the bay."
    "Maya Armitage: (Your throat tight) 'I miss the sound of your hammer on wood.' (You try to keep the sentiment bright enough to be breathable.) 'I'm here, doing what I can.'"

    jonah_reyes "You're doing more than I could stand. I should be there. But—' (His voice breaks and he swallows) '—I can't make them wait. I have mouths to feed, Maya."

    maya_armitage "I know.' (What else is there to say that isn't an accusation or a plea?) 'We both chose survival in different forms."

    jonah_reyes "I don't want to lose us on this.' (His words are small but they tremble with meaning.) 'Distance is a thief."
    "Maya Armitage: (You imagine his hands—callused, still—making knots in new rope. You imagine him learning a different city's tides of labor.) 'We will be frayed,' you admit, truth like a rag. 'But if we stop cataloguing,"
    "if we stop caring, then the place that made us will be gone in every way that matters.'"
    "Jonah Reyes: (Long pause) 'Promise me you'll keep your shoulder sometimes for me.' (He sounds like a man asking for a dock in a storm.)"
    "Maya Armitage: (You want to promise more than you can guarantee) 'I'll do my best. I can't promise I won't be angry. I can't promise you won't go. But I'll keep recording. I'll come when I can.'"

    jonah_reyes "That's something.' (He laughs, and it is small and sad.) 'Take care of Nan for me."

    maya_armitage "Always."
    "The call ends with no grand resolution—only the precise, measured ache of two people trying to tether themselves to each other as tides pull them apart. You fold the phone away and pull your scarf up"
    "against the damp. The promenade hums with cleanup crews and volunteers; the new storefronts open their doors to staged tours for the curious and disbelieving. The town functions in two registers: the lived cove and the"
    "curated cove, each reflecting the other imperfectly."
    "You sit on the edge of the boardwalk and open your waterproof notebook. Pages are full of lists: names, times, funding flows, photographs zipped into sleeves. You draw a line through a budget table where a"
    "marsh allocation was redirected. You sketch Nan's hands, the way they find each other and hold. The notation is not neat; it is a ledger and a prayer."
    "Grief comes in slow increments. People will rebuild, some in relocated clusters where safety is purchased but community is attenuated. Some will leave. Some traditions will be moved or die. The managed retreat saved lives where"
    "it succeeded, and that matters; but the cultural fabric—threads of song, smell, boat-building know-how—was severed in places, and those gaps will not stitch themselves back with money alone."
    "At dusk you walk the promenade one last time before the official ribbon-cutting—an act that will frame the town in a new narrative. You stand under one of the new lights and watch the polished crowd"
    "arrive: city officials, investors, ribbon in gloved hands. Behind them, a cluster of relocated families stands with quilts over their shoulders, the makers of the actual work reduced to witnesses."
    "You think of the possible endings you once modeled—the happy, the bittersweet, the true—and now see how our choices, no matter how heroic in intent, met a force larger than a single town's planning commission. The"
    "result is a bitter, necessary calculus: some survive with dignity; some survive through displacement; some lose not only property but the mnemonic threads that let a place be itself."

    "You close your notebook and pull Nan's hand into yours. Jonah's voice lives in a small corner of the page, written in his hand in a note you keep folded" "Keep some of it just for us."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A low chord; a long exhale]
    hide maya_armitage
    hide jonah_reyes

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_6 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Scissors snip; a polite, rehearsed applause; the distant sea, indifferent]
    "You rise as the ribbon falls and the cameras flash. Someone hands you a program—fancy paper with glossy photos that sweeten the wound. You refuse the offered drink and instead walk the edge where the promenade"
    "meets the water. The tide advances with the patience of an indifferent god. You place your palm on the railing and feel the cold that comes from long seasons."
    "You are here. You will keep documenting. You will keep naming. Some will stay and stitch together a future with graft and grit. Others will leave. Jonah may come back for visits; perhaps you'll meet at"
    "the margins, two maps overlaid imperfectly. Love persists—tired, stretched, and not whole—but it is not enough to restore what was lost."

    "You breathe the salty air and hold the moment in the only way you can: with witness. You make an entry in your notebook that reads, simply" "Shoreline farewells catalogued—names, dates, circumstances. Truth kept."
